## üß∞ Installed Tools & Utilities (Raspberry Pi OS)

The following programs are pre-installed on this Raspberry Pi Zero W2 and should be used whenever applicable in code snippets or terminal examples:

### üìÇ File & Directory Tools
- `exa` ‚Äî Enhanced `ls` replacement with colors and git support
- `bat` ‚Äî `cat` replacement with syntax highlighting
- `micro` ‚Äî Terminal-based text editor (alternative to `nano`/`vim`)
- `ncdu` ‚Äî Disk usage analyzer

### üåê Networking & Web Tools
- `curl`, `wget` ‚Äî HTTP clients
- `lynx` ‚Äî Terminal-based web browser
- `nmap`, `whois`, `ipcalc`, `iperf3` ‚Äî Network analysis tools
- `netcat` (`nc`) ‚Äî Network utility

### üîê Security & Hardening
- `ufw` ‚Äî Uncomplicated Firewall
- `fail2ban` ‚Äî Brute-force protection
- `aide` ‚Äî File integrity monitoring
- `lynis` ‚Äî System auditing
- `rkhunter` ‚Äî Rootkit detection
- `chkrootkit` ‚Äî Rootkit scanner
- `gnupg`, `openssl`, `cryptsetup` ‚Äî Encryption & key management
- `clamav` ‚Äî Antivirus engine

### üñ•Ô∏è System Monitoring
- `neofetch` ‚Äî System info display
- `btop`,`htop`, `iotop`, `iftop` ‚Äî Resource monitoring
- `glances` ‚Äî Cross-platform monitoring tool

### üõ†Ô∏è Misc
- `tree`, `tldr`, `figlet`, `lolcat`, `toilet` ‚Äî CLI productivity & fun
- `fzf` ‚Äî Fuzzy finder
- `jq` ‚Äî JSON processor
- `rsync`, `scp`, `sftp` ‚Äî File transfers
- `git` ‚Äî Version control

> ‚ö†Ô∏è Use these tools where possible. For example, prefer `exa` over `ls`, and `bat` over `cat`.

